Specti is able to detect information about natural disasters and accidents from social media such as Twitter, Instagram, and Facebook, analyze the content, determine the truthfulness of the information, and distribute it to the companies using it.
"We broadly consider "crisis" to be a situation that has a negative impact that can stop or stagnate social activities" (Murakami Kenjiro, CEO), a crisis management support service that visualizes various crises occurring in Japan and overseas.
The NHK broadcaster during the Kumamoto earthquake in April 2016 was the first major use of Specti, and subsequently, the movement of adoption spread rapidly among companies.
It is said that not only television stations and newspapers, but also companies that support social infrastructure such as electricity, gas, and transportation, and more than 350 companies in Japan, including local governments throughout the country, are currently using Specti.
Analyze the post to determine the type of "crisis" and the place where it occurred
Specti delivers information in four steps: "Collection of information", "Analysis and content classification", "Title assignment", and "Truth and falsehood assessment".
The company that uses the information must specify the region where it will collect the information (prefecture, city, town, etc.) and the category of crisis (disaster or accident, etc.) in advance.
Specti collects posts that fall under its designation using an API provided by social media.
Next, the collected posts are analyzed and categorized into text, images, and videos.
For example, if a video shows a fire engine, black smoke rising from a building, and orange flames from a room, then it is classified as a "fire".
In addition, images of vehicles that have been rolled over are classified as "traffic accidents" and images of roads covered with water are classified as "road floods".
Specti also estimates the location of disasters and accidents.
"We often don't know where to find the post, so we're combining various information to make an estimate," says Murakami.
For example, if a road sign or signboard is projected onto an image or video, the information about the place name is extracted from it and matched with the place name database to identify the place.
