The Ministry of Internal Affairs and Communications is conducting a full-scale review of the Mobile Number Transfer System (MNP), which allows users to change their mobile phone numbers as they are.
At the meeting of experts on 21 March, the government announced its policy to revise the guidelines for the MNP, which was established in 2004.
The specific issues are diverse, such as the way MNP fees are paid and whether to detain transferees.
With the expected reaction from the telecommunications companies, attention will be focused on whether it will lead to the promotion of healthy market competition.
The dark side of communication companies where unlimited mobile phone transfers are so far away The user fee for the initial introduction of MNP in 2006 was 2,000 yen, but now it is 3,000 yen.
The MNP fee revenue of the three major mobile communications companies is estimated at 15.9 billion yen annually.
The Ministry of Internal Affairs and Communications (MIC) on March 21 listed the current situation regarding MNP at the "Working Group on Verification of Competition Rules" (WG) meeting of experts to discuss the competitive environment in the telecommunications market.
The time required for consumers to receive the MNP reservation number when transferring to other telecommunications companies was also highlighted.
The main entrance to the station is from the station building, but due to the high traffic, the station is open from 9 a.m. to 8 p.m.
The WG documents clearly stated that the principle of all-day response was the direction for future consideration.
The company also sees problems in retaining people who wish to transfer to MNP by giving them points from mobile phone companies.
This is because the judgement that excessive retention can impede fair competition.
"We need to have time to explain the economic benefits, get permission from the users, and issue a number to the users who do not agree to it," says Shunichi Kita, a partner at Nomura Research Institute who is a member of the WG.
However, among the issues raised, there is a structural problem with MNP fees, namely, "The higher the MNP fees, the less customers can be outsourced, so it is difficult to motivate customers to lower them aggressively" (a person in charge of the Ministry of Internal Affairs and Communications).
If a company takes the lead in lowering MNP fees, it is also concerned that the company's efforts will not be rewarded, as customers will be more likely to leave the company.
The Ministry of Internal Affairs and Communications also points out that many countries overseas do not require user fees for MNP, and this may be the case in Japan.
